SIMPLE: purple
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Purple
<hw>Pur"ple</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Purples</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>purpre</ets>,
<ets>pourpre</ets>, OF. <ets>purpre</ets>, <ets>porpre</ets>,
<ets>pourpre</ets>, F. <ets>pourpre</ets>, L. <ets>purpura</ets> purple
fish, purple dye, fr. Gr. <?/ the purple fish, a shell from the purple
dye was obtained, purple dye; cf. <?/ dark (said of the sea), purple,
<?/ to grow dark (said of the sea), to be troubled; perh. akin to L.
<ets>furere</ets> to rage, E. <ets>fury</ets>: cf. AS.
<ets>purpure</ets>. Cf. <er>Porphyry</er>, <er>Purpure</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A color formed by, or resembling that formed by, a
combination of the primary colors red and blue.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Arraying with reflected <qex>purple</qex> and gold⟦br⟧
The clouds that on his western throne attend.</q> <rj><qau>
Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The ancient words which are translated <xex>purple</xex>
are supposed to have been used for the color we call <xex>crimson</xex>.
In the gradations of color as defined in art, <xex>purple</xex> is a
mixture of red and blue. When red predominates it is called
<xex>violet</xex>, and when blue predominates,
<xex>hyacinth</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Cloth dyed a purple color, or a garment of such
color; especially, a purple robe, worn as an emblem of rank or
authority; specifically, the purple rode or mantle worn by Roman
emperors as the emblem of imperial dignity; <as>as, to put on the
imperial <ex>purple</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou shalt make the tabernacle with ten curtains of fine twined
linen, and <qex>purple</qex>, and scarlet.</q> <rj><qau>Ex. xxvi.
1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Hence: Imperial sovereignty; royal rank, dignity, or
favor; loosely and colloquially, any exalted station; great
wealth.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧He was born in the <xex>purple</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Gibbon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A cardinalate. See <er>Cardinal</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any species of large butterflies,
usually marked with purple or blue, of the genus <gen>Basilarchia</gen>
(formerly <gen>Limenitis</gen>) <as>as, the banded <ex>purple</ex>
(<spn>Basilarchia arthemis</spn>).</as> See <xex>Illust.</xex> under
<er>Ursula</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any shell of the genus
<gen>Purpura</gen>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf><fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>See
<er>Purpura</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>A disease of wheat. Same as
<er>Earcockle</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Purple</xex> is sometimes used in composition, esp.
with participles forming words of obvious signification; as,
<xex>purple</xex>-colored, <xex>purple</xex>-hued,
<xex>purple</xex>-stained, <xex>purple</xex>-tinged,
<xex>purple</xex>-tinted, and the like.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>French purple</b></col>. <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <cd>Same as
<er>Cudbear</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Purple of Cassius</b></col>. <cd>See
<er>Cassius</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Purple of mollusca</b></col>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a coloring matter derived from certain mollusks,
which dyes wool, etc., of a purple or crimson color, and is supposed to
be the substance of the famous Tyrian dye. It is obtained from Ianthina,
and from several species of Purpura, and Murex.</cd> -- <col><b>To be
born in the purple</b></col>, <cd>to be of princely birth; to be
highborn.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Purple</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Purple
<hw>Pur"ple</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Exhibiting or
possessing the color called purple, much esteemed for its richness and
beauty; of a deep red, or red and blue color; <as>as, a <ex>purple</ex>
robe</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Imperial; regal; -- so called from the color having
been an emblem of imperial authority.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hide in the dust thy <qex>purple</qex> pride.</q>
<rj><qau>Shelley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Blood-red; bloody.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>May such <qex>purple</qex> tears be alway shed.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I view a field of blood,⟦br⟧
And Tiber rolling with a <qex>purple</qex> blood.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Purple bird</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the
European purple gallinule. See under <er>Gallinule</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Purple copper ore</b></col>. <fld>(Min.)</fld> <cd>See
<er>Bornite</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Purple grackle</b></col>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the crow blackbird. See under
<er>Crow</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Purple martin</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Martin</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Purple sandpiper</b></col>. <cd>See
under <er>Sandpiper</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Purple shell</b></col>.
<cd>See <er>Ianthina</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Purple</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Purple
<hw>Pur"ple</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Purpled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Purpling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To make purple; to dye of purple
or deep red color; <as>as, hands <ex>purpled</ex> with
blood</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When morn⟦br⟧
<qex>Purples</qex> the east.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Reclining soft in blissful bowers,⟦br⟧
<qex>Purpled</qex> sweet with springing flowers.</q> <rj><qau>
Fenton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Purpleheart</ent>⟦br⟧
